    "instruction": "Load the four CSV files (metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, error_logs.csv). For each file produce a compact summary only: 1) total row count, 2) minimum timestamp, 3) maximum timestamp, 4) up to top 20 distinct cmdb_id values, and 5) up to top 20 distinct KPI/trace/log name values (use metric->kpi_name, trace->trace_name, log->log_name). For error_logs.csv show up to top 20 distinct message values instead of KPI names. Do not print full rows. Keep outputs compact and labeled by filename."
}

{
    "analysis": "We loaded all four CSVs and produced a compact summary. Metrics cover 04:00–05:00 (so full-series thresholds can be computed); traces and logs cover the incident window 04:30–04:59; error_logs contains a single error at 2022-03-21T04:57:13+08 with cmdb_id 'frontend-2' and message 'severity: error, message: request error'. This suggests a likely problem around frontend-2 at ~04:57:13, but we must follow the prescribed workflow: compute global thresholds for metric component-KPI series (using full available series), then filter to the incident window (2022-03-21 04:30:00+08 to 2022-03-21 05:00:00+08) and detect anomalies. We should prioritize metric-based anomaly counts per component-KPI to narrow candidates before inspecting traces/logs. Next, we need a bounded metric-scan output: per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the full series, then within the incident window count points above P95 and below P5, report earliest anomaly timestamp within the window, total points in window, and basic stats. Return top up to 20 component-KPIs ranked by anomaly count so we can focus further analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair compute using the full available series: count, global P95, global P5, global max, global min. Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 04:30:00+08 through 2022-03-21 05:00:00+08 inclusive. For each pair, compute: number of points in the window, number of points > P95 (count_above_p95), number of points < P5 (count_below_p5), earliest timestamp in window where value > P95 or < P5 (earliest_anom_ts), and the maximum value-in-window and minimum value-in-window. Produce a compact table of up to top 20 pairs ranked by max(count_above_p95, count_below_p5) (show pairs with any anomalies first). For each row show: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, global_P5, count_in_window, count_above_p95, count_below_p5, earliest_anom_ts, max_in_window, min_in_window. Keep outputs bounded to these columns and at most 20 rows. Store the full intermediate per-pair table in a kernel variable for follow-up but do not print it."
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed global P95/P5 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full metric series and filtered those series to the incident window (2022-03-21 04:30:00+08 through 2022-03-21 05:00:00+08). The top-20 anomalous (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs show many services/pods with both high and low excursions (each showing 3 points >P95 and 3 points <P5 across the 31-minute window). Notable candidates include frontend-0, frontend-2, frontend2-0, currencyservice2-0, cartservice2-0, checkoutservice2-0, and adservice2 (and some container.node-6 metrics). The error_logs file also contains a single error at 2022-03-21T04:57:13+08 for cmdb_id 'frontend-2' stating 'severity: error, message: request error'. From metrics alone there are multiple simultaneous anomalies; next we must aggregate anomalies to identify which component(s) exhibit the largest, earliest, and most widespread anomalies so we can then use traces and logs to localize the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the per-pair intermediate table saved in the kernel (if named per_pair_table or per_pair_df — otherwise recompute the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) table as you did before), aggregate anomalies by cmdb_id as follows: for each cmdb_id compute total_anom = sum(count_above_p95 + count_below_p5) across its KPIs; num_kpis_with_anom = number of KPIs with (count_above_p95+count_below_p5)>0; earliest_anom_ts = earliest non-null earliest_anom_ts among its KPIs; total_count_in_window = sum(count_in_window); and identify the top_kpi (the kpi_name with the largest (count_above_p95+count_below_p5)) including top_kpi_anom_count and that KPI's max_in_window and min_in_window. Return a compact table (store it in kernel as cmdb_anom_summary) with columns: cmdb_id, total_anom, num_kpis_with_anom, earliest_anom_ts, total_count_in_window, top_kpi_name, top_kpi_anom_count, top_kpi_max_in_window, top_kpi_min_in_window. Limit to top 20 rows ordered by total_anom descending."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metric anomalies by cmdb_id for the incident window. The results show many frontend pods (frontend2-0, frontend-0, frontend-2, frontend-1) and several service pods (checkoutservice2-0, adservice2, currencyservice2-0, productcatalogservice variants, cartservice2-0, etc.) with the highest aggregated anomaly counts. Each top cmdb_id has many KPIs with anomalies (num_kpis_with_anom is large) and their top KPI anomaly counts are non-trivial. Notably, an external hint from error_logs (previously observed) shows a single error at 2022-03-21T04:57:13+08 for cmdb_id 'frontend-2' with message 'severity: error, message: request error'. Metrics alone indicate a broad anomaly footprint across many frontends and downstream services; therefore we cannot yet pick a single root cause component. Next we must use traces to decide which faulty component is the most downstream faulty component in call chains and whether frontend-2 is implicated by traces around the error time. Trace analysis should compute global thresholds per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using full trace series, then look for anomalies within the incident window and return compact ranked results for the top candidate cmdb_ids (bounded).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Take the top 10 cmdb_id candidates from cmdb_anom_summary (the kernel variable created previously). For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair in trace.csv compute the global P95 and P5 using the full available series. Then filter trace rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 04:30:00+08 through 2022-03-21 05:00:00+08. For each pair compute: count_in_window, count_above_p95, count_below_p5, earliest_anom_ts (earliest timestamp in-window where value>P95 or value<P5), max_in_window, min_in_window. Return a compact table (store it as trace_anom_top) of up to top 20 rows ordered by max(count_above_p95, count_below_p5) descending. Show columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_P95, global_P5, count_in_window, count_above_p95, count_below_p5, earliest_anom_ts, max_in_window, min_in_window. Keep output bounded to these columns and at most 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We ran trace-level anomaly analysis for the top candidate cmdb_ids from metrics. The trace results show consistent short-duration excursions (typically 2 points above P95 and 2 below P5 per trace series) across many frontend-related trace series (frontend-0 prominently) and some currencyservice2-0 series. Earliest anomalous trace points appear as early as 2022-03-21T04:30:00+08 (some frontend->currencyservice traces) and several anomalies cluster around 04:31–04:41+08. Combined with metric aggregation, the most affected cmdb_ids are frontend2-0, frontend-0, checkoutservice2-0, frontend-2, frontend-1. The error_logs previously showed a single error at 2022-03-21T04:57:13+08 for cmdb_id 'frontend-2' with message 'severity: error, message: request error'. Metrics and traces indicate widespread anomalies among frontends and downstream services across the entire incident window, so we cannot yet pick a single root cause. Next, we must analyze logs: compute global thresholds for log KPIs (using full series) and detect anomalies within the incident window, and also inspect raw error_logs rows in the window to correlate exact error timestamps and messages.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv. 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, log_name) in log.csv compute global P95 and global P5 using the full available series. Then filter log rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 04:30:00+08 through 2022-03-21 05:00:00+08. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) produce: count_in_window, count_above_p95, count_below_p5, earliest_anom_ts (first in-window time where value>P95 or value<P5), max_in_window, min_in_window. Return a compact table (store in kernel as log_anom_top) of up to top 20 rows ordered by max(count_above_p95,count_below_p5) descending and show columns: cmdb_id, log_name, global_P95, global_P5, count_in_window, count_above_p95, count_below_p5, earliest_anom_ts, max_in_window, min_in_window. 2) Also extract all rows from error_logs.csv within the same incident window (show up to 20 rows) and store them as error_logs_window. Return both results in the execution output."
}

{
    "analysis": "We ran log-level anomaly detection and extracted error_logs in the incident window. Results: log.row_count anomalies appear across many services (frontends and downstream services) with small but consistent excursions (typically 2 samples above P95 and 2 below P5). There is one concrete error log at 2022-03-21T04:57:13+08 for cmdb_id 'frontend-2' with message 'severity: error, message: request error'. Metrics and traces earlier showed widespread short anomalies among frontend pods (frontend2-0, frontend-0, frontend-2, frontend-1) and downstream services; traces indicate anomalous behavior starting as early as ~04:30–04:31+08 while the error log for frontend-2 is at ~04:57+08. At this stage we have narrowed suspects to frontend pods but have not yet identified a single fault segment (consecutive KPI anomalies) that clearly acts as the root cause. According to the workflow, the next step is fault identification: find consecutive anomaly sub-series (not isolated spikes) for a high-priority candidate to determine the exact occurrence time and resource reason. We should inspect frontend-2’s metric KPIs (using global thresholds computed from full series) and identify multi-minute anomaly runs (length >= 2) within the incident window, and rank them by severity and duration.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Focus on cmdb_id 'frontend-2'. Using metric.csv, for each (frontend-2, kpi_name) first compute global P95 and P5 using the full available series (no filtering). Then filter the metric points to the incident window 2022-03-21 04:30:00+08 through 2022-03-21 05:00:00+08. Mark each in-window point as anomalous if value > global_P95 (breach_type='high') or value < global_P5 (breach_type='low'). Group anomalous points into consecutive-minute segments (consecutive timestamps differing by 60 seconds). Discard isolated single-point anomalies (keep segments with count_points >= 2). For each segment produce: kpi_name, breach_type, start_ts, end_ts, duration_minutes, count_points, max_in_segment, min_in_segment, global_P95, global_P5, and severity_ratio defined as max(|value-global_P95|/global_P95) for high breaches or max(|global_P5-value|/global_P5) for low breaches. Return up to top 20 segments ordered by severity_ratio desc then duration_minutes desc. Store full segment table in kernel (e.g., frontend2_fault_segments). Keep output bounded to these columns and <=20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected recommendationservice (recommendationservice-0/1/2 and recommendationservice2-0) metric anomalies for the incident window. The results show concurrent anomalies across resource (CPU, fs), network, and mesh/jaeger-related KPIs. Notable points: CPU and cfs_periods anomalies cluster ~04:33–04:36, mesh/jaeger and network anomalies appear earlier and throughout the window, and fs_usage + container_last_seen show multiple above-P95 events at ~04:58. Combined with earlier findings for frontend-2 (an extreme high spike on mesh.source.frontend.recommendationservice at 04:55 and many low-type mesh drops at 04:57 with an error log at 04:57:13), we currently have two plausible scenarios: (A) frontend-2 generated an abnormal request spike at ~04:55 that overloaded recommendationservice or the mesh, causing downstream drops and the frontend error at ~04:57; or (B) recommendationservice pods themselves experienced resource or lifecycle anomalies (CPU/fs/last_seen) that caused degraded responses and led to frontend retries/errors. To disambiguate, we must perform fault identification on the recommendationservice pods: find consecutive anomaly segments (not isolated spikes), their exact start times and severity, and whether their first anomalous points precede or follow frontend-2's spike at ~04:55. This will let us determine which component first deviated and hence the likely root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For recommendationservice pods (recommendationservice-0, recommendationservice-1, recommendationservice-2, recommendationservice2-0) run fault-segmentation similar to frontend-2: using metric.csv compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) from the full series; filter points to the incident window 2022-03-21 04:30:00+08 through 2022-03-21 05:00:00+08; mark in-window points where value>global_P95 (breach_type='high') or value<global_P5 (breach_type='low'); group anomalies into consecutive-minute segments (timestamps consecutive by 60s); discard single-point segments; for each segment produce: cmdb_id, kpi_name, breach_type, start_ts, end_ts, duration_minutes, count_points, max_in_segment, min_in_segment, global_P95, global_P5, severity_ratio (as defined earlier). Return and store up to top 20 segments ordered by severity_ratio desc then duration desc in a kernel variable named recsvc_fault_segments. Limit output to the specified columns and <=20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected recommendationservice-2 filesystem and last_seen metrics for the incident window and found no abrupt fs or heartbeat jumps: fs_usage rose slowly and container_last_seen values were stable. Previously, fault-segmentation identified strong multi-point anomalies for recommendationservice-2 clustered ~04:55–04:58+08 (both very large high spikes on mesh/jaeger KPIs and multiple low drops on mesh request/response and network KPIs). Frontend-2 showed a very large high spike at 04:55–04:56+08 (mesh.source.frontend.recommendationservice.*) and an error log at 04:57:13+08. Recommendationservice-2 also shows lifecycle-like signals (container_last_seen & fs_usage) with above-P95 events at ~04:58. From these artifacts: recommendationservice-2 exhibits severe multi-KPI faults beginning ~04:55, followed by frontend-2 errors at ~04:57. There is no evidence of an immediate container restart (last_seen stable) or abrupt FS exhaustion; network/mesh-related KPIs show strong anomalies. To decide root cause we need to confirm which component's fault segment started first (earliest anomalous segment) — recommendationservice-2 or frontend-2 — using the already computed fault-segment tables, so we can identify the most likely origin and exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel fault-segment tables (recsvc_fault_segments and frontend2_fault_segments), find the single earliest anomalous segment for recommendationservice-2 and the single earliest anomalous segment for frontend-2. For each component return one row with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, breach_type, start_ts, end_ts, duration_minutes, count_points, severity_ratio. Order is not important; limit output to these two rows only. Keep outputs compact and do not print other tables."
}

I conclude the most likely root cause based on the telemetry correlation (metrics, traces, logs, and fault-segmentation).

